# Assignment 1 Security Update

I, Demetre, updated my existing Spring Boot wardrobe project by integrating Spring Security into the already submitted application. I did not create a new project. I added authentication, authorization, role-based access control, encrypted password storage, and method-level security.

## Login Credentials

The application seeds these test accounts when the backend starts:

```text
ADMIN account
Username: admin
Password: Admin123!
Role: ADMIN

USER account
Username: demetre
Password: User12345!
Role: USER
```

All seeded and registered passwords are stored with `BCryptPasswordEncoder`, not plain text.

## Security Summary

I added persistent user roles with `USER` and `ADMIN` values. Registered users receive the `USER` role by default. The seeded `admin` account receives the `ADMIN` role.

I updated `SecurityConfig` to include a `SecurityFilterChain`, public endpoints, authenticated endpoints, role-restricted endpoints, login behavior, logout behavior, CORS, and method security.

I enabled method-level security with `@EnableMethodSecurity` and added this method restriction:

```java
@PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")
public List<UserDto> getAllUsers()
```

## Public Endpoints

These endpoints are available without logging in:

```text
POST /api/auth/register
POST /api/auth/login
GET  /swagger-ui/**
GET  /v3/api-docs/**
GET  /uploads/**
GET  /h2-console/**
```

## Protected Endpoints

These endpoints require an authenticated session:

```text
GET  /api/me
POST /api/auth/logout
GET  /api/profile
PUT  /api/profile
GET  /api/pieces
POST /api/pieces
GET  /api/pieces/{id}
PUT  /api/pieces/{id}
DELETE /api/pieces/{id}
GET  /api/outfit/random
```

## ADMIN-Only Functionality

Only users with the `ADMIN` role can access these management endpoints:

```text
GET    /api/users
POST   /api/users
GET    /api/users/{id}
PUT    /api/users/{id}
DELETE /api/users/{id}
GET    /api/profiles
POST   /api/profiles
GET    /api/profiles/{id}
PUT    /api/profiles/{id}
DELETE /api/profiles/{id}
GET    /api/clothing-pieces
GET    /api/clothing-pieces/{id}
```

The frontend also shows the current logged-in role in the header after login.

## Login and Logout

Login is handled through:

```text
POST /api/auth/login
```

Logout is handled through:

```text
POST /api/auth/logout
```

After logout, the session is invalidated and the `JSESSIONID` cookie is deleted.

## CSRF Explanation

CSRF protection is disabled in `SecurityConfig` because this project uses a separate React frontend that sends JSON and multipart requests to the Spring Boot API from another origin. The API still requires authenticated sessions for protected routes, CORS is restricted to configured frontend origins, and this decision is also commented in the security configuration.

